			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2010</a> paper:</span><br><i>Canonical Method Names for Java: Using Implementation Semantics to Identify Synonymous Verbs</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/EinarWHøst.html">Einar W. Høst</a>, <a href="../profile/BjarteMØstvold.html">Bjarte M. Østvold</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-642-19440-5_14">10.1007/978-3-642-19440-5_14</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5b.html"><span class="tagM">T5B: Language Description Analysis</span></a><ul><li> The contribution is a language-oriented analysis of code to infer canonical method names from implementation semantics.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t6g.html"><span class="tagL">T6G: Socio-technical</span></a><ul><li> It targets developer-facing naming conventions and their cognitive/communication aspects in code bases.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5e.html"><span class="tagL">T5E: Empirical Evaluation</span></a><ul><li> The approach is validated empirically by mining/analyzing Java code and assessing synonym detection.
</li></ul></li></ul>
